{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-94b0f905f0021a7a", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tSemantic Homogenization in Italian Popular\n2\tMusic: A Diachronic Analysis\n3\tLorenzo Canale1,2*† , Stefano Scotta1,3*† and Alberto Messina1,4*\n4\t\n5\tarXiv:2607.04832v1 [cs.CL] 6 Jul 2026\n6\t\n7\t1\n8\t\n9\tCentro Ricerche, Innovazione Tecnologica e Sperimentazione, RAI, Via\n10\tGiovanni Carlo Cavalli 6, Turin, 10138, Italy.\n11\t2\n12\tORCID: 0000-0002-7556-595X; Google Scholar: hsgYvg0AAAAJ.\n13\t3\n14\tORCID: 0000-0003-1078-2985; Google Scholar: mJRjh1sAAAAJ.\n15\t4\n16\tORCID: 0000-0002-8262-2449; Google Scholar: hmd7668AAAAJ.\n17\t\n18\t*Corresponding author(s). E-mail(s): lorenzo.canale@rai.it;\n19\tstefano.scotta@rai.it; alberto.messina@rai.it;\n20\t†\n21\tThese authors contributed equally to this work.\n22\tAbstract\n23\tIn recent years, studies have revealed a decline in semantic variety across popular music lyrics, particularly in English-language songs on streaming platforms\n24\tlike Spotify. This research examines whether a similar trend can be observed in\n25\ta different linguistic and cultural context: the lyrics of all finalist songs from the\n26\t75 editions of the Sanremo Music Festival, Italy’s most renowned music competition. What sets this work apart is the development of a flexible and efficient\n27\tmethodology for tracking changes in semantic similarity over time, which can\n28\tbe applied to different datasets to study similar phenomena. Drawing on a combination of full-text, segment-based, topic-based, and word-level analyses, the\n29\tapproach leverages both embedding techniques and large language models. When\n30\tapplied to the Sanremo corpus, this framework reveals a gradual move toward\n31\tincreasing semantic uniformity, echoing the global patterns identified in previous\n32\tstudies. These findings underscore the value of natural language processing tools\n33\tin uncovering long-term shifts in musical language and cultural expression.\n34\tKeywords: Semantic similarity, Embedding models, Song lyrics analysis, Large\n35\tlanguage models (LLMs), Natural Language Processing, Sanremo Festival\n36\t\n37\t1\n38\t\n39\t\fThis preprint has not undergone peer review (when applicable) or any postsubmission improvements or corrections. The Version of Record of this article is\n40\tpublished in Journal of Computational Social Science, and is available online at\n41\thttps://doi.org/10.1007/s42001-026-00468-1.\n42\t\n43\t1 Introduction\n44\tUnderstanding textual meaning has long been a central concern in both literary studies\n45\tand computational linguistics. In literary theory, semantics is the study of how words\n46\tand structures convey meaning, encompassing aspects such as denotation, connotation,\n47\tand intertextuality [1, 2]. Computational approaches to semantics aim to model these\n48\tnuances through mathematical representations, with word and sentence embeddings\n49\temerging as a powerful technique to capture semantic similarities between texts [3, 4].\n50\tSemantic embeddings map textual units (e.g., words, sentences, or entire documents) into high-dimensional vector spaces, where distances between vectors correspond to semantic similarity [5]. Models such as Word2Vec [6], GloVe [7], and\n51\ttransformer-based embeddings [8] have demonstrated remarkable capabilities in\n52\tcapturing linguistic patterns, including synonymy, topical coherence, and stylistic\n53\tvariation.\n54\tIn this study, we present two main contributions:\n55\t\n56\t• A methodology that enables the analysis of semantic similarity within a musical\n57\tcollection by selecting specific variables for comparison, such as time. By combining\n58\tdifferent similarity measures, such as full-text, portion-based, topic-based, and wordbased similarity—using embedding models and large language models (LLMs), this\n59\tapproach provides a more comprehensive analysis.\n60\t• An in-depth analysis of the Sanremo Festival lyrics over time: we apply the methodology to analyze lyrical diversity at the Sanremo Festival, a major Italian music\n61\tcompetition. Our findings indicate a trend of increasing semantic homogeneity in\n62\tlyrics over time, suggesting a shift in artistic expression that may reflect broader\n63\tcultural and industry-wide influences.\n64\t\n65\t2 Motivation\n66\tApart from its inherent entertainment nature, the Sanremo Festival [9], being one\n67\tof Italy’s most prestigious and longest-running music competitions, has long served\n68\tas a significant cultural event in Italy, reflecting and influencing the country’s social,\n69\tpolitical, and cultural landscapes and capturing the nation’s attention during the week\n70\tof the show. This is proved by the huge audience rates the Festival collects over the\n71\tyears, making it the most important annual television event. This prominence as a\n72\tsocial event has fostered several studies, which highlight how the festival has evolved\n73\tfrom reinforcing traditional values to addressing contemporary societal issues [10–12]\n74\tas well as acting as a vehicle for political messages and populism-orientated discourse\n75\ton pressing national and global topics [13, 14] and a platform to discuss important\n76\tthemes related to psychological health issues in modern society [15].\n77\t\n78\t2\n79\t\n80\t\fFig. 1 The image provides an overview of the methodology presented in the paper, illustrating\n81\thow semantic similarity is analyzed across different years of the Sanremo Music Festival. The top\n82\tpart of the image displays a macro-matrix representing the pairwise similarity between all years in\n83\tthe dataset, calculated using a topic-based method. Each cell represents a pair of years, with color\n84\tintensity indicating average topic similarity (extracted via Gemini from lyrics). The bottom left\n85\tquadrant zooms in on a specific pair of years, 1956 and 2004, as an example of the detailed pairwise\n86\tyear analysis conducted. It shows a sub-matrix where each cell represents the topic similarity between\n87\tevery song from 1956 (rows) and 2004 (columns). To the right, an example compares a 1956 song\n88\t(”Anima gemella”) with one from 2004 (”L’uomo volante”), illustrating individual-level analysis. For\n89\tthese two songs, the English translations of the topics are shown. Embedding vectors of the Italian\n90\ttopic descriptions are computed, and their cosine similarity is calculated. A similar procedure, adapted\n91\tfor each method, was applied to the other four semantic similarity analyses; for example, Full-Text\n92\tSimilarity uses complete lyrics for embedding and similarity calculations.\n93\t\n94\t3\n95\t\n96\t\fIt should be therefore evident that this study, conducted on the evolution and\n97\tsimilarity of lyrics for the entire series of the Sanremo Festival, adds significant value\n98\tto the current state of the art by providing a case study of long-term, genre-specific\n99\tlyrical trends and similarities within a highly influential cultural event. Furthermore,\n100\twhile many studies explore the evolution of lyrics in popular music globally, a study\n101\tfocusing on the Sanremo Festival provides a specific cultural lens. By analyzing the\n102\tlyrics of songs performed over decades at Sanremo, it is possible to track shifts in\n103\tlanguage use, thematic focus, and emotional expression within the context of Italian\n104\tculture, offering a deeper understanding of the Italian musical landscape.\n105\t\n106\t3 Related work\n107\tRecent research has highlighted a marked simplification in the musical structure of\n108\tpopular songs over time. For instance, Di Marco et al. [16] analyzed over 20,000 compositions using tools from network science, revealing a significant reduction in musical\n109\tcomplexity across diverse genres. Similarly, Hamilton and Pearce [17] examined U.S.\n110\tchart-topping melodies from 1950 to 2023 and identified a decreasing trend in melodic\n111\tvariety and unpredictability. While these studies focus on the structural and harmonic\n112\tdimensions of music, our work diverges by addressing the evolution of lyrics.\n113\tPrevious approaches to analyzing musical texts have applied various methods,\n114\tincluding word2vec and bag-of-words. For instance, [18] focused on rap lyrics, using\n115\tword embeddings to capture semantic meaning. On the other hand, [19] introduced\n116\tgraph-based representation to analyze and interpret popular music lyrics.\n117\tIn this paper, a key factor driving the adoption of transformer embeddings and\n118\tsemantic similarity measures is their alignment with human perception. In particular, [20] recently found a significant correlation between semantic similarity scores\n119\tand perceptual similarity judgments, suggesting that embedding-based approaches can\n120\teffectively approximate human cognitive evaluations of textual similarity; while they\n121\tutilized the all-MiniLM-L6-v21 model, in our analysis we use more recent embedding models (see Section 5) because of their superior performance in benchmark\n122\tevaluations2 (see [21]).\n123\tIn [22] the authors employed embeddings also to trace trends in textual evolution,\n124\thighlighting the increasing significance of semantic embeddings in the humanities.\n125\tTheir work supports some hypotheses from literary studies while offering fresh\n126\tperspectives on the development of early modernism in German poetry.\n127\tFurthermore, in [23] it was discovered that lyrics have become simpler over time\n128\tacross several dimensions. While the authors analyzed lyrical trends using handcrafted\n129\tdescriptors—such as lexical diversity, structural patterns, and rhyme characteristics—our approach differs by utilizing semantic embeddings. At the conclusion of their\n130\tstudy, the authors emphasize the broader implications of lyrical analysis, noting that\n131\tsong lyrics remain an underexplored but valuable resource for understanding cultural\n132\tartifacts and societal shifts. Our research aligns with this perspective, demonstrating\n133\thow semantic similarity analysis can reveal evolving lyrical patterns, thus contributing\n134\t1\n135\t2\n136\t\n137\thttps://huggingface.co/sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2\n138\thttps://huggingface.co/spaces/mteb/leaderboard\n139\t\n140\t4\n141\t\n142\t\fto the broader discourse on cultural and artistic transformations in music. Additionally, our findings, derived from a prominent Italian music festival, reaffirm the trends\n143\tobserved in their more general dataset.\n144\t\n145\t4 Overview\n146\tThis work is structured as follows. Section 5 introduces the dataset we collected and\n147\tthe embedding models used throughout the experiments, along with the corresponding notation. Section 6 presents the techniques employed to analyze the evolution of\n148\tsemantic similarity over the years in the lyrics of songs performed at the Sanremo\n149\tFestival finals. Each subsection focuses on a specific type of analysis. See Figure 1 for\n150\tan example that shows in general how the analysis is performed. Finally, in Section 7,\n151\twe discuss the results of the experiments described in Section 6. Section 8 concludes\n152\twith a brief discussion of potential future work in this area.\n153\t\n154\t5 Dataset and Embeddings Used\n155\tFor each year Y ∈ Y = {1951, . . . , 2025} in which the Sanremo festival took place, we\n156\tcollected the lyrics of the nY finalist songs, denoted as l1Y , . . . , lnYY .\n157\tTo analyze the similarities between songs, we considered a set E of different textual\n158\tembedding models. Specifically, we considered E = {i, o, c}, where:\n159\t\n160\t• i represents the sentence transformer model intfloat/multilingual-e5-large3 ,\n161\tsee [24] for details;\n162\t• o corresponds to OpenAI’s embedding model text-embedding-3-large4 ,\n163\t• c denotes colbert-xm5 , see [25, 26] for details.\n164\tNote that hereinafter we will generally talk about similarity between embeddings.\n165\tWhen the embeddings considered are i and o we call similarity the standard cosine\n166\tsimilarity. When the embedding considered is c, since the “MaxSim” similarity S ,\n167\tcommonly used for c, is not symmetric (see [25, 26]), we call similarity between two\n168\tc-embeddings A and B , the quantity 21 [S (A, B ) + S (B, A)].\n169\t\n170\t6 Cross-Year Analysis of Semantic Similarity\n171\tIn this section, we present different approaches for analyzing the similarities between\n172\tsongs across the years. The goal is to compute, for each pair of years (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y ×Y , a\n173\tn\n174\tmeasure that quantifies the average semantic similarity between the lyrics lY1 a , . . . , lYaYa\n175\tnY\n176\tand lY1 b , . . . , lYb b . This allows us to examine the evolution of lyrical similarity over time.\n177\t\n178\t6.1 Full-Text Similarity\n179\tWe first analyze song similarities using embeddings computed from the full lyrics.\n180\tGiven an embedding model α ∈ E , we construct, for each pair of years (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y ,\n181\t3\n182\t4\n183\t5\n184\t\n185\thttps://huggingface.co/intfloat/multilingual-e5-large\n186\thttps://openai.com/index/new-embedding-models-and-api-updates/\n187\thttps://huggingface.co/antoinelouis/colbert-xm\n188\t\n189\t5\n190\t\n191\t\fan nYa ×nYb similarity matrix FYαa ,Yb , where each entry represents the cosine similarity\n192\tbetween the embeddings (obtained with α) of the songs from Ya and Yb . An example\n193\tis shown in Figure 2.\n194\t\n195\ti\n196\tFig. 2 Example of the similarity matrix F1951,1960\n197\t, where values are normalized such that the\n198\tminimum is 0 and the maximum is 1. Rows and columns correspond to the titles of the finalist\n199\tsongs from 1951 and 1960, respectively. This grid shows the similarity in the full text of each song\n200\tpairing, with warmer colors indicating more alike lyrics and cooler colors indicating less similarity.\n201\tThe normalization allows for easy comparison of relative similarities.\n202\t\n203\tNext, we compute similarity measures for all possible year pairs (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y ,\n204\tavoiding the diagonal when Ya = Yb . Specifically, for each embedding model α ∈ E ,\n205\twe derive the following matrices:\n206\tα\n207\t\n208\t• F mean which is built evaluating for each (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y , the mean of all values in\n209\tα\n210\tFYαa ,Yb (excluding the diagonal if Ya = Yb ) obtaining a first |Y| × |Y| matrix. F mean\n211\tis obtained normalizing the latter matrix in such a way that that the minimum\n212\tvalue is 0 and the highest is 1.\n213\tα\n214\tα\n215\t• F med which is analogous to F mean but considering the median (instead of the mean)\n216\tα\n217\tsimilarity score, then normalized as F mean .\n218\tα\n219\t• F q whose element corresponding to (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y is the proportion of elements\n220\tof FYαa ,Yb that exceeds the q -quantile threshold, computed across all song pairs in\n221\tthe dataset. Selecting a high value of q , it represents the percentage of song pairs for\n222\teach couple of years which are more similar than the majority of the other possible\n223\tpairs.\n224\t6\n225\t\n226\t\fSee Figure 3 for an example.\n227\t\n228\ti\n229\t\n230\tFig. 3 Matrix F 0.75 , as defined in Section 6.1, shows the percentage of song pairs between any two\n231\tyears where the full lyrics exceed the similarity of 75% of all other song pairs. Warmer colors indicate\n232\ta larger proportion of unusually high lyrical similarity between those years.\n233\t\n234\t6.2 Portion-Based Similarity\n235\tA potential limitation of full-text analysis is that two songs might be highly similar\n236\teven if their overall similarity score is not particularly high. Instead of comparing\n237\tentire lyrics, we introduce a measure that assigns greater importance to similar textual\n238\tsegments.\n239\tFor each song lYi , where Y ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nY }, we segment it into portions\n240\ti\n241\tp(lY ) = p1 , . . . , pmiY , where miY ≥ 1, ensuring that lYi is reconstructed from the\n242\tordered union of this portions. The portions are extracted using an LLM (namely\n243\tgemini-1.5-flash6 ) prompted to segment lyrics into portions made up of more than\n244\tone sentence. Hence, to evaluate the similarity between two songs lYi a and lYj b , for some\n245\tYa , Yb ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nYa }; j ∈ {1, . . . , nYb }, we consider their portions p(lYi a ) and\n246\tp(lYj b ) and compute the similarity between the α-embedding of all the couples (pi , pj ),\n247\t6\n248\t\n249\thttps://ai.google.dev/gemini-api/docs/models\n250\t\n251\t7\n252\t\n253\t\ffor α ∈ E , pi ∈ p(lYi a ) and pj ∈ p(lYj b ), obtaining a miYa × mjYb matrix Πα (lYi a , lYj b ). The\n254\telement (u, v ) of the matrix Πα (lYi a , lYj b ) is the similarity between the α-embedding of\n255\tthe u-th portion of lYi a and the one of the v -th portion of lYj b . A concrete example of\n256\tsimilar portions of text could be found in Table 2.\n257\tThen, to visualize similarities between songs for a couple of years (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y\n258\tbased on their parts, we define the nYa × nYb matrix PYα,k\n259\t, for some arbitrary small\n260\ta ,Yb\n261\t(see Remark 1) positive integer k , whose element (i, j ) is the sum of the k highest\n262\tvalues of the matrix Πα (lYi a , lYj b ). In the matrices PYα,k\n263\twith Ya = Yb we avoid the\n264\ta ,Yb\n265\tdiagonal values. The matrix PYα,k\n266\tis the analogous, but reasoning on songs’portions,\n267\ta ,Yb\n268\tof the matrix FYαa ,Yb (full-text similarity).\n269\tAs we did in Section 6.1, in order to have matrices that allow us to visualize some\n270\tsimilarity measures across years, we define the following (normalized) |Y|×|Y| matrices\n271\tα,k\n272\tα,k\n273\tα,k\n274\tα\n275\tP mean , P med , P q , which are defined for any α ∈ E , exactly as, respectively, F mean ,\n276\tα\n277\tα\n278\tF med , F q but using the matrices PYα,k\n279\tinstead of FYαa ,Yb , for (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y . See\n280\ta ,Yb\n281\tFigure 4 for an example.\n282\tRemark 1 k must be smaller than the minimum of {miYa mjYb : i ∈ {1, . . . , nYa }, j ∈\n283\t{1, . . . , nYb }}.\n284\t\n285\t6.3 Topic-Based Similarity\n286\tAnother approach to evaluating semantic similarity is through the analysis of lyrics\n287\ttopics. To achieve this, in a first step we identify the primary topics tYi for each song\n288\tliY , where Y ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nY }. The identification process is done using a LLM\n289\t(namely gemini-1.5-flash) prompted to, given the lyrics of a song, return a list\n290\tof the main topics treated in the text. Once topics are extracted for each song, we\n291\tcompute the similarity between the topics tYi a and tYj b of two generic songs liYa and\n292\tljYb , for Ya , Yb ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nYa }, j ∈ {1, . . . , nYb }. This is done by converting\n293\tthe lists of topics into strings, which are then embedded using α ∈ E . The similarity\n294\tbetween two songs based on the topics is thus the similarity between the α-embedding\n295\tof these strings. Therefore it is straightforward to build, for each (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y , the\n296\tnYa ×nYb matrix TYαa ,Yb containing the topic similarities between all the song presented\n297\tat the Sanremo festival in Ya and Yb (avoiding the diagonal if Ya = Yb ). TYαa ,Yb is\n298\tanalogous to FYαa ,Yb and PYα,k\n299\t(defined in Sections 6.1 and 6.2), but topics based.\n300\ta ,Yb\n301\tOnce we compute all the matrices TYαa ,Yb , in order to analyze the evolutions of topics\n302\tα\n303\tα\n304\tsimilarity across years, we compute the (normalized) |Y| × |Y| matrices T mean , T med ,\n305\tα\n306\tα\n307\tα\n308\tα\n309\tT q exactly as done in Section 6.1 for, respectively, F mean , F med , F q but using the\n310\tmatrices TYαa ,Yb instead of FYαa ,Yb , for (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y . See Figure 5 for an example.\n311\t\n312\t6.4 Word-Based Similarity\n313\tIn this section, we adopt a different analytical approach, shifting from embeddingbased models to a purely statistical evaluation of word occurrences. By focusing on\n314\t8\n315\t\n316\t\fo,3\n317\t\n318\tFig. 4 Matrix P mean , as defined in Section 6.2, presents the average similarity based on the top 3\n319\tmost similar sections of lyrics between songs from any two years. Warmer colors suggest a greater\n320\thomogeneity in the lyrical content, specifically within the most comparable segments, between the\n321\tsongs of those two years.\n322\t\n323\twords co-occurrence patterns across lyrics and years, it is possible to assess whether\n324\tthe results gained through embedding-based techniques align with the statistical ones.\n325\tFor each lYi , for Y ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nY }, we considered both the lyric as-is and\n326\ta normalized one ˜lYi obtained converting all verbs to their infinitive form, transforming\n327\tall text to lowercase, and reducing all nouns and adjectives to their singular form.\n328\tThe normalized text ˜lYi is obtained prompting a LLM (namely gemini-1.5-flash)\n329\tto transform the text lYi as explained above.\n330\ti\n331\tto its\n332\tRemark 2 Although in principle the normalization of the text to pass from a lyric lY\n333\t7\n334\ti\n335\tnormalized version ˜\n336\tlY could be done even relying on simpler methods (like the spaCy python\n337\tlibrary [27]) rather than LLM, we observed that even when using Italian-specific models,\n338\tthe resulting forms were often suboptimal—especially for verbs, which were lemmatized into\n339\tunexpected or non-infinitive forms. For this reason, we opted for an LLM-based approach,\n340\twhich, in our experiments, produced more consistent and intuitive results for the data at\n341\thand. However, this was not a formal evaluation, but rather a practical choice based on\n342\tmanual inspection.\n343\t7\n344\t\n345\thttps://spacy.io/\n346\t\n347\t9\n348\t\n349\t\fTo focus only on significant words, we filter each lyric (both original and normalized) to retain only verbs, nouns, and adjectives. This filtering is based on automatic\n350\tpart-of-speech (PoS) tagging performed using the spaCy Python library with the\n351\tit core news lg model, which is specifically trained for Italian. The extraction is carried out in two ways: preserving repeated words or not, using the transformations ρ\n352\tand ρ̃ on a generic text T :\n353\t\n354\t• ρ(T ) = list of all significant words in T with repetition;\n355\t• ρ̃(T ) = list of all significant words in T without repetition.\n356\tSo, for example, if the initial text is T = “my Home is a very sweet home”, its\n357\tcleaned version T̃ would be “my home be a very sweet home”. Then ρ(T ) = [Home,\n358\tis, sweet, home] = ρ̃(T ), ρ(T̃ ) = [home, be, sweet, home], ρ̃(T̃ ) = [home, be, sweet].\n359\tIn this case, the “similarity” between two lyrics lYi a and lYj b , for Ya , Yb ∈ Y and\n360\ti ∈ {1, . . . , nYa }, j ∈ {1, . . . , nYb }, is given by ρ(lYi a ) ∩ ρ(lYj b ) (resp. ρ(˜lYi a ) ∩ ρ(˜lYj b ) on\n361\tthe normalized text), if we want to give more weight to the repeated words, and by\n362\tρ̃(lYi a ) ∩ ρ̃(lYj b ) (resp. ρ̃(˜lYi a ) ∩ ρ̃(˜lYj b )) otherwise.\n363\tNow, that we defined the similarity for this type of analysis, we build for each pair\n364\tof years (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y four different matrices WYι a ,Yb , ι ∈ {1, 2, 3, 4}, containing\n365\tthe similarities between the songs in Ya and Yb defined as above, considering the four\n366\t\n367\tc\n368\t\n369\tFig. 5 Matrix T med , as defined in Section 6.3, illustrates the median similarity of the main themes\n370\tdiscussed in songs between any two years. Warmer colors indicate a higher thematic similarity.\n371\t\n372\t10\n373\t\n374\t\fcombination of as-is or normalized text and intersection with or without repetition.\n375\tMore precisely, the similarity between lYi a and lYj b will be represented in WY1a ,Yb , WY2a ,Yb ,\n376\tWY3a ,Yb , WY4a ,Yb as, respectively, ρ(lYi a ) ∩ ρ(lYj b ), ρ̃(lYi a ) ∩ ρ̃(lYj b ), ρ(˜lYi a ) ∩ ρ(˜lYj b ), ρ̃(˜lYi a ) ∩\n377\tρ̃(˜lYj b ). This is summarized in Table 1.\n378\tTable 1 Notation for the WYι a ,Yb ,\n379\tι ∈ {1, 2, 3, 4} and (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y,\n380\tobtained through the intersections\n381\tof ρ and ρ̃ transformations, applied\n382\tto lyrics in their original (“as-is”)\n383\tand normalized forms.\n384\tρ\n385\t\n386\tρ̃\n387\t\n388\tas-is\n389\t\n390\tWY1a ,Yb\n391\t\n392\tWY2a ,Yb\n393\t\n394\tnormalized\n395\t\n396\tWY3a ,Yb\n397\t\n398\tWY4a ,Yb\n399\t\n400\tThen, to analyze the word-based similarities, defined above, across the years, we\n401\tproceed as in the previous sections, see Section 6.1 for details, to calculate, for each\n402\tι\n403\tι\n404\tι\n405\tι ∈ {1, 2, 3, 4} the (normalized) |Y|×|Y| matrices W mean , W med , W q from the matrices\n406\tWYι a ,Yb for all (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y .\n407\t\n408\t7 Results and Discussion\n409\tTo analyze the evolution of similarity (according to the different definitions) over\n410\tα\n411\tα,3\n412\tα\n413\tι\n414\tyears, we computed the following matrices F τ , P τ , T τ , W τ , for α ∈ {i, o, c}, ι ∈\n415\tα\n416\t{1, 2, 3, 4} and τ ∈ {mean, med, 0.75}. Then, because the matrices F τ (and analoα,3\n417\tα\n418\tι\n419\tgously P τ , T τ , W τ for ι ∈ {1, 2, 3, 4}),for α ∈ E , show the same pattern of similarities\n420\tat the varying of τ ∈ {mean, med, 0.75}, we decided to focus on the case τ = mean.\n421\tMoreover, to proceed with just one matrix for P\n422\teach type of similarityP\n423\tanalysis conι\n424\tα\n425\t4\n426\tW\n427\tF\n428\t:=\n429\tsidered, we defined the matrices W mean :=\n430\t,\n431\tmean\n432\tτ\n433\tι=1\n434\tα∈E F mean ,\n435\tP\n436\tP\n437\t3\n438\tα3\n439\tα\n440\tP mean := α∈E P mean and T mean := α∈E T mean . These latter matrices take into\n441\taccount all the different shades of similarity that the various embeddings or text normalization techniques capture in the different similarity analyses. To verify that all\n442\tthese different analyses lead to the same conclusions, we computed the Pearson correlation coefficients between the matrices defined above. The results, visible in Figure\n443\t7, showing high values of correlations for all the possible pairs, suggesting that each\n444\tanalysis leads to the same conclusions.\n445\tHence, to visualize an overall similarity analysis across years, we defined the |Y| ×\n446\t3\n447\t|Y| matrix Z = F mean + P mean + T mean + W mean , which then we normalized in\n448\torder that the minimum values is 0 and the maximum 1, obtaining the final matrix\n449\tZ , visible in Figure 8.\n450\tThe matrix Z suggests that the correlation across the years is increasing with the\n451\tyears, becoming relatively bigger when computed on the last decades. Also the average\n452\t\n453\t11\n454\t\n455\t\f12\n456\t\n457\tSong 2\n458\t\n459\tG. Martinelli\n460\tIl gigante d’acciaio\n461\t(2020)\n462\t\n463\tTricarico\n464\tVita tranquilla\n465\t(2008)\n466\t\n467\tAnna Tatangelo\n468\tLibera\n469\t(2015)\n470\t\n471\tSong 1\n472\t\n473\tGino Paoli\n474\tUn altro amore\n475\t(2013)\n476\t\n477\tVasco Rossi\n478\tVita spericolata\n479\t(1983)\n480\t\n481\tE. De Crescenzo\n482\tVia con me\n483\t(1983)\n484\t\n485\tI... want a quiet life.\n486\tBecause since I was born...\n487\tit’s been\n488\tDesperate... reckless...\n489\tYet free... truly boundless.\n490\tI should... no, I shouldn’t...\n491\t\n492\tLooking at fears.\n493\tBurning inside the sun.\n494\tAnd feeling that with you\n495\tI am free.\n496\tFree.\n497\tLike a cloud in the wind\n498\tThat sways.\n499\tUnique, unique.\n500\tLike moonlight\n501\twhen it shines.\n502\tA cloud in the sky\n503\twhen the sun is out.\n504\tSwaying in the air,\n505\tit drifts on its own.\n506\tYour fears drift away.\n507\tAdventures are forgotten.\n508\tBut how can you stand\n509\tbeing alone at night?\n510\t\n511\tThere won’t be\n512\tAnother time, another time.\n513\tThere won’t be\n514\tAnother time, yet again.\n515\t\n516\tThere won’t be another love.\n517\tThere won’t be another time.\n518\tThe one missing on my path\n519\tWas you,\n520\tand no matter what\n521\tThere won’t be another love.\n522\t\n523\tI want a reckless life...\n524\tI want a rude life...\n525\tI want an excessive life...\n526\t\n527\tLyrics 2 (Translated)\n528\t\n529\tLyrics 1 (Translated)\n530\t\n531\tTable 2 Examples of high lyrical similarity between segments. Original lyrics were in Italian and translated into English.\n532\t\n533\t\f3\n534\t\n535\tFig. 6 Matrix W mean , as defined in Section 6.4, shows the average overlap in significant normalized\n536\twords (nouns, verbs, adjectives in base form) used in the lyrics between any two years. Warmer colors\n537\tsuggest greater lexical similarity.\n538\t\n539\tsimilarity of the song presented in each year (diagonal of Z ) appears to be growing\n540\twith the years, as it is clear from the plot in Figure 9, suggesting that the average\n541\tsimilarity across the single editions of the festival is also growing with the years.\n542\tMoreover, it appears that the songs presented in the festival in the first years are\n543\tless similar to all the others with respect to the recent ones. This is even more clear\n544\tlooking at the plots in Figure 9.\n545\t\n546\t8 Conclusion and future work\n547\tIn conclusion, this paper introduces a novel methodology, leveraging semantic embeddings and large language models, to analyze the evolution of lyrical diversity in musical\n548\tcollections. Applying this framework to the Sanremo Festival, a prominent Italian\n549\tmusic competition, the study reveals a discernible trend towards increasing semantic homogeneity in lyrics over recent years. This finding is consistent across various\n550\tsimilarity measures, including full-text, portion-based, topic-based, and word-based\n551\tanalyses, as confirmed by high Pearson correlation coefficients between these different\n552\tapproaches. This research not only provides a quantitative perspective on the evolution of Sanremo lyrics but also highlights the efficacy of semantic embeddings in\n553\tuncovering nuanced trends within cultural artifacts.\n554\t13\n555\t\n556\t\f3\n557\t\n558\tFig. 7 Pearson correlation coefficients between F mean , P mean , T mean and W mean . The high values\n559\t(warmer colors) suggest a strong positive agreement between the different lyrical similarity analysis\n560\tmethods (full text, portions, topics, and words), indicating consistent patterns in the results.\n561\t\n562\tThis study opens avenues for future research:\n563\t\n564\t• Developing a Python Framework: We plan to release a Python framework\n565\tbased on our methodology that allows researchers to analyze how song similarity\n566\tevolves based on a given variable (e.g., the release year of the songs). This tool would\n567\tfacilitate large-scale investigations into the temporal dynamics of lyrical similarity\n568\tacross different datasets.\n569\t• Incorporating Musical Difference Metrics: In [20], the authors introduced\n570\tthe Musical Difference metric, which has shown an even stronger correlation with\n571\thuman perceptions of lyrical similarity than standard semantic similarity measures.\n572\tFuture work should explore integrating this metric into our similarity analysis.\n573\t• Validating the Methodology on External Datasets: Since [23] has made their\n574\tdataset publicly available, it would be valuable to apply our methodology to their\n575\tdataset and verify whether our approach yields similar findings.\n576\tBy addressing these directions, we aim to refine our methodology, improve its\n577\tinterpretability, and contribute to a broader understanding of how lyrical similarity\n578\tevolves in different musical contexts.\n579\t\n580\tDeclarations\n581\tFunding\n582\tNo funding was received for conducting this study.\n583\t\n584\t14\n585\t\n586\t\fFig. 8 Matrix Z, as defined in Section 7, sum and normalize the results from all our analysis methods\n587\tto show the general lyrical similarity between any two years, considering full text, key sections,\n588\tthemes, and word choice. Warmer colors indicate a stronger overall similarity.\n589\t\n590\tFig. 9 In dashed red the evolution across years of the average similarity within the single Sanremo\n591\tFestival editions (diagonal of Z). In blue the mean of the average similarities for each year against\n592\tall the others (sum of Z rows).\n593\t\n594\t15\n595\t\n596\t\fCompeting interests\n597\tThe authors have no relevant financial or non-financial interests to disclose.\n598\t\n599\tConflict of interest\n600\tOn behalf of all authors, the corresponding author states that there is no conflict of\n601\tinterest.\n602\t\n603\tData availability\n604\tThe authors do not hold reproduction rights for the song lyrics; therefore, only the\n605\tyear of release, title, author, and interpreter of each song are provided (see Section 5).\n606\t\n607\tReferences\n608\t[1] Allan, K.: Concise Encyclopedia of Semantics. Elsevier, Netherlands (2009)\n609\t[2] Panagiotidou, M.-E.: An introduction to the semantics of intertextuality. Journal\n610\tof Literary Semantics 41(1), 47–65 (2012) https://doi.org/10.1515/jls-2012-0003\n611\t[3] Harispe, S., Ranwez, S., Janaqi, S., Montmain, J.: Semantic Similarity from Natural Language and Ontology Analysis. Springer, Cham (2022). https://doi.org/\n612\t10.1007/978-3-031-02156-5\n613\t[4] Rapaport, W.J.: Syntactic semantics: Foundations of computational naturallanguage understanding. In: Dietrich, E. (ed.) Thinking Computers and Virtual\n614\tPersons, pp. 225–273. Academic Press, University of Michigan (1994). https:\n615\t//doi.org/10.1016/B978-0-12-215495-9.50015-6\n616\t[5] Li, B., Zhou, H., He, J., Wang, M., Yang, Y., Li, L.: On the Sentence Embeddings from Pre-trained Language Models. https://doi.org/10.18653/v1/2020.\n617\temnlp-main.733\n618\t[6] Mikolov, T., Chen, K., Corrado